863_gold_teamwork.solution:
(Analysis by  Dhruv Rohatgi )
This problem can be solved by dynamic programming. Let $dp[i]$ be the optimal
sum of skill levels achievable by the first $i$ cows, assuming that the last
team ends at cow $i$. If we knew that $k$ was the size of the last team (among
the first $i$ cows), then the optimal sum of skill levels would be
$$dp[i-k] + \max_{0 \leq j < k} s_{i-j}.$$
But the size of the last team could be anywhere from $1$ to $K$. So we must try
all possible sizes, and set $dp[i]$ to the best sum of skills achieved.
This immediately yields an $O(NK^2)$ algorithm, since there are $N$ states, $K$
transitions, and each transition takes $O(K)$ time to compute. However, we can
speed up the transitions by maintaining $$\max_{0 \leq j < k} s_{i-j}$$ as $k$
is increased. Updating the maximum takes $O(1)$ time, so each transition is now
$O(1)$, for an overall time complexity of $O(NK)$. This is fast enough.

#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;

int N,K;
int A[10000];
int dp[10000];

int main()
{
	cin >> N >> K;
	for(int i=0;i<N;i++)
		cin >> A[i];
	dp[0] = A[0];
	for(int i=1;i<N;i++)
	{
		int mx = A[i];
		for(int j=i;j>=0 && i+1-j <= K; j--)
		{
			mx = max(mx, A[j]);
			if(j==0) dp[i] = max(dp[i],mx*(i+1-j));
			else dp[i] = max(dp[i],dp[j-1] + mx*(i+1-j));
		}
	}
	cout << dp[N-1] << '\n';
}

